hine-Westphalia, or in western Poland (Jelenia Góra). In some instances the German surname may be topographic, from the same elements.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): artificial name composed of German <i>Hirsch</i> ‘deer’ + <i>Berg</i> ‘mountain, hill’ (see 1 above). Compare   Hershberg   and   Hirshberg  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hershberg","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Hyman, Yehoshua.","Americanized form of German <b>Herschberg</b> (see   Herschberger  ) or   Hirschberg  , and a variant of the same Jewish surnames."]},{"name":"Hirshberg","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Isadore.","Americanized form of German   Hirschberg  , and a variant of the same Jewish surname."]},{"name":"Hirschberger","meanings":["German: habitational name for someone from any of several places called   Hirschberg  .","German: altered form of Swiss German   Hersberger  . Compare   Harshbarger  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): mainly an artificial name composed of German <i>Hirsch</i> ‘deer, hart’ + <i>Berg</i> ‘mountain, hill’ + the agent suffix <i>-er</i>, but possibly also habitational in some cases (see 1 above)."]}]},{"name":"Gerhard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>gēr</i>, <i>gār</i> ‘spear’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Gerhard I von Hirschberg was born in 1163, in Sulzbach, Bavaria, Germany as the son of Hartwig III von Grogling and VON RIENECK UND MAINZ. He had at least 1 son with Sophie von Sulzbach. He died about 1188, at the age of 26."},"et":{"1163–ca 1188":"1163–umbes 1188","1163–1188":"1163–1188","1138–1227":"1138–1227","1160–1232":"1160–1232","–1139":"–1139","–Female":"Surnud","1139":"1139","1227":"1227","1138":"1138","1232":"1232","1188":"1188","1163":"1163","ca 1188":"umbes 1188","1160":"1160","Sulzbach, Oberpfalz, Bavaria, Germany":"Sulzbach, Bayern, Saksamaa"},"fi":{"1163–ca 1188":"1163–noin 1188","1163–1188":"1163–11